Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm wide wedges (no need to peel). Pop them onto a
large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{},
then toss to coat.

Spread out in a single layer. 

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-35%minutes}.
Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, finely chop the @flat leaf parsley{1} (stalks and all).

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

In a large #bowl{}, combine the garlic, @dried oregano{1%tsp} and half the parsley.
Mix in the @panko breadcrumbs{10%g}, @salt{1/4%tsp} and @water{2%tbsp}, then add
the @British beef mince{240%g}.

Season with pepper and mix together with your hands.

Roll into even-sized balls, then shape into 1cm thick burgers, 1 per person.

> TIP: The burgers will shrink a little during cooking. IMPORTANT: Wash your
> hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

Pop the burgers and @British streaky bacon{4%slices} onto a baking tray and bake
on the middle shelf of your oven until cooked through, ~{12-15%minutes} (use two
trays if necessary).

> IMPORTANT: The burgers are cooked when no longer pink in the middle. Cook bacon
> thoroughly.

Meanwhile, halve the @baby plum tomatoes{125%g} and pop them into a bowl.

Add the remaining parsley along with the @red wine vinegar{12%ml} and
@olive oil{2%tbsp} for the dressing. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and mix
together.

Just before the wedges are cooked, halve the @burger buns{2}. Pop them onto a
baking tray and into the oven to warm through, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Once the bacon is cooked, set aside on a #plate{} lined with #kitchen paper{}.

When everything's ready, spread some @mayonnaise{2%tbsp} on each bun base. Add
the burger, 2 bacon rashers, then top with the bun lid.

Serve with the potato wedges and parsley tomato salad.

Enjoy!